		<section id="b9c623b60388444498f4d5afc993f983">
			<title>Features of Digital Images</title>
			<body>
				<p id="b80e221f0cb14df3bb367aee4a2fdf13">In this section, we look at the basic features of digital images. You see images on computers and phones all the time. We look behind the curtain to see how images are put together. What looks like an ordinary image on your device&apos;s display is actually a file consisting of many numbers.</p>
				<section id="d7ad2579877f4a6bb687aad209f507f8">
					<title>Pixels</title>
					<body>
						<p id="bc8d72ba25874a54a70cf78501f6d915">Here is an image of some yellow flowers:</p>
						<image id="b9136a297165401aaa7cf45295436ebc" src="../webcontent/flowers.jpg" alt="yellow flowers" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
							<caption>
								<p id="a04ee6d40d1942bb80a1421fc92fa50a" />
							</caption>
							<popout enable="false"></popout>
						</image>
						<p id="f2e07e631fc94aa895b9e415e9b1f5f5">Zooming in on the upper-left flower, we can see that it is actually made of many tiny square <em style="italic">pixels</em>, each showing just one color. Looking at the image normally, we see the whole scene. By zooming, we see the tiny, artificial-looking, one-color pixels that make up the image.</p>
						<image id="a4eaf4d4f140424fb7dcd865af2e02be" src="../webcontent/flowers-pixels.png" alt="zoom in to see pixels" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
							<caption>
								<p id="c611dcaec5ce4158b6ea7915568dfa95" />
							</caption>
							<popout enable="false"></popout>
						</image>
						<p id="abdaad3f694a429cb5cd7ca6f9bcb4ef">The size of an image can be expressed in pixels; for example, an image might be 800 pixels wide by 600 pixels high. The total number of pixels is just the product: 800 * 600 = 480,000. A <em style="italic">megapixel</em> is 1 million pixels, so 480,000 pixels is about 0.5 megapixels. Digital cameras today produce images with several megapixels per image, say 8000 Ã— 6000, for about 48 megapixels.</p>
					</body>
				</section>
				<section id="dabcb83a8a3d40ca9355ea9cc3037ec2">
					<title>Pixel x,y Coordinates</title>
					<body>
						<p id="cc31462028914525955c3ffb212cc66f">We do not work extensively with individual x,y coordinates. You just need to see that there is an x,y grid covering the image, so every pixel has its own x,y coordinate.</p>
						<p id="ea1a60096d7a42108dd2a69ce07204a4">The <em style="italic">origin</em> pixel is x=0, y=0, which is at the upper-left of the image. The <em style="italic">x</em> numbers increase going to the right of the origin, so x=1, y=0 is one pixel to the right. Coordinates such as x=1, y=0 are often just written in parenthesis, like so: (1, 0). The <em style="italic">y</em> numbers increase going down from the origin, so y=0 is the top row, y=1 is the next row down, and so on.</p>
						<image id="fb17006424e24e518c4ac7988dc53931" src="../webcontent/image-diagram1.png" alt="grid of pixels with x,y coordinates" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
							<caption>
								<p id="ba2df1943cd1445ab56d0d334bce4a67" />
							</caption>
							<popout enable="false"></popout>
						</image>
						<p id="b075cec1d5f54752aa1fecfb6ab12f4d">The key point is that there is an x,y grid, and every pixel has its own x,y coordinates within the grid. The (0, 0) pixel is at the upper left.</p>
					</body>
				</section>
			</body>
