		<section id="dc2fdf9971a4433090e79ed6b6e65c89">
			<title>Newton&apos;s Color Prism</title>
			<body>
				<p id="c3a60481641c443a9ad91cb227392b35" />
				<image id="e2ab6b7c703f4a14b46749194468ec99" src="../webcontent/newton-prism.jpg" alt="newton prism experiment" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
					<caption>
						<p id="e71e6c58b12f490d9f741e4e8bde172a" />
					</caption>
					<popout enable="false"></popout>
				</image>
				<p id="bb271bab622540ba917dd47b09993b85">Sir Isaac Newton did the famous prism experiment, showing that white light is made up of a spectrum of pure colored light. The photograph above shows a triangular prism. White sunlight is coming from the left into the prism, which splits up (<em style="italic">defracts</em>) the light. Coming out of the prism is a continuous range of pure colors, seven of which are commonly named as the colors of the rainbow: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet (ROY G BIV). Imagine running the experiment backwards: combining various colored lights to form white light. We will do this later.</p>
				<section id="dc2304d11ba3455d8a52b3ef4136bb88">
					<title>RGB Color Scheme: Red, Green, Blue</title>
					<body>
						<p id="a45efebb574f438086618bac5da05d6e">Each pixel shows a single color. How is a single color represented?</p>
						<p id="f4752062a402427d810820318f2008e7">The red, green, blue (RGB) scheme is a common way to represent a single color, and that&apos;s what we use here. The idea is that any desired color can be formed by combining red, green, and blue light, varying the brightness of each to produce the desired color.</p>
						<section id="c4d23ae56d4b4fa4810c4d8f465265fa">
							<title>RGB Explorer</title>
							<body>
								<p id="c56b0150c390442891eb900b102d2398">The best way to see how RGB works is to try it with this <activity_link title="u-course_resources-m-course_resources-p-rgb_explorer" idref="u-course_resources-m-course_resources-p-rgb_explorer" target="self" purpose="checkpoint">RGB Explorer</activity_link> page. The page has three sliders, one each for red, green, and blue. Move the sliders around to see how levels of red, green, and blue can produce any color.</p>
								<p id="c957abb9cb6041ca9b6dd24d0b577f99">The RGB scheme is based on combining three types of colored <em style="italic">light</em>. This is different from the paint-combining techniques you may have used. Forming colors with light works differently than it does with paint, and light-forming is what we&apos;re doing here.</p>
							</body>
						</section>
						<section id="fbb65c4326624c7eac325d797894d804">
							<title>RGB: Three Numbers</title>
							<body>
								<p id="e98644e25e0648c880d8cda32f7984ee">In RGB, a color is defined as a mixture of pure red, green, and blue lights of various strengths. Each of the red, green, and blue light levels is encoded as a number in the range 0 through 255, with 0 meaning zero light and 255 meaning maximum light.</p>
								<p id="e13f92dbe1f7422d88215e21765b2c38">For example, red=255, green=100, blue=0 defines a color in which red is maximum, green is medium, and blue is not present at all, resulting in a shade of orange. In this way, any color can be produced by specifying the brightness in the range 0 through 255 for the red, blue, and green components of the pixel.</p>
