				<section id="d4c0ab7165cb4cc9aa722d4f111aab6d">
					<title>Image Diagram with RGB</title>
					<body>
						<p id="b4941d04b0774f7392fddc2bbd853dc6">Now we have all the elements to represent an digital image as numbers. The image is made of many pixels. Each pixel has five numbers:</p>
						<ul id="f4263e5edd8444c5b9488ed6628d88d2">
							<li>
								<p id="a5017dab58964db1ab54e04cbb11ab98">
									<em>x,y numbers:</em> The location of every pixel is defined by its <em style="italic">two</em> x,y numbers.</p>
							</li>
							<li>
								<p id="b22fda336fb444e48c7a2bbb3dd394d5">
									<em>RGB numbers:</em> The color shown by every pixel is defined by its <em style="italic">three</em> RGB numbers.</p>
							</li>
						</ul>
						<image id="dad45b23dfb04ed8b07a84b4a9183fc8" src="../webcontent/image-diagram2.png" alt="grid of pixels with x,y coordinates and RGB numbers" style="inline" vertical-align="middle">
							<caption>
								<p id="c3f10a070b1e4d58b27583bbea0ca000" />
							</caption>
							<popout enable="false"></popout>
						</image>
					</body>
				</section>
				<section id="bb4445fb256d47f6a5d157954d38a53f">
					<title>Digital Atomization</title>
					<body>
						<p id="c38414f5ca5948928ce2702334d377a4">We have seen how a digital image is represented in the computer: the image is broken down into tiny pixels. Then each pixel is broken down into its three RGB numbers, each in the range 0 to 255. So ultimately, the whole image is represented as a mass of little numbers. This &quot;atomization&quot;, representing something big by a mass of little numbers, is a common pattern in computer systems.</p>
					</body>
				</section>
